'''Francis Michael Christ''' (born 7 June 1955) is an [[Americans|American]] [[mathematician]], specializing in [[harmonic analysis]], [[partial differential equation]]s, and [[several complex variables]].<ref name=UCB>{{cite web|title=Michael Christ (home page)|website=Mathematics Department, University of California, Berkeley|url=https://math.berkeley.edu/people/faculty/f-michael-christ}}</ref><ref name=Notices>{{cite journal|author=Jackson, Allyn|title=1997 Bergman Prize Awarded|date=April 1997|volume=44|issue=4|pages=464–465|journal=Notices of the AMS|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/199704/people.pdf}}</ref> He is known for the [[Christ–Kiselev maximal inequality]].

==Biography==
He received in 1977 from [[Harvey Mudd College]] his bachelor's degree<ref name=UCB/> and in 1982 from the [[University of Chicago]] his PhD under the supervision of [[Alberto Calderón]] with thesis ''Restrictions of the Fourier transform to submanifolds of low codimension''.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=9337|title=F. Michael (Francis) Christ}}</ref> At [[Princeton University]] (where he worked with Elias M. Stein), Christ was from 1982 to 1984 an instructor and from 1984 to 1986 an assistant professor. He was at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) from 1986 to 1988 an associate professor and from 1988 to 1996 a full professor. In 1996 he became a full professor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=Notices/>

Christ was a Sloan Fellow for the academic year 1986–1987. In 1990 in Kyoto he was an invited speaker at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Christ, M.|title=''In:'' Proceedings of the International Congress of Mathematicians, Kyoto, 1990|chapter=Precise analysis of <math>\overline{\partial_b}</math> and <math>\overline{\partial}</math> on domains of finite type in <math>\mathbb{C}</math><sup>2</sup>{{space|1}}|volume=vol. 1|pages=859–877|chapter-url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.467.4109&rep=rep1&type=pdf}}</ref> In 1997 he shared with [[David E. Barrett]] the [[Stefan Bergman Prize]].<ref name=Notices/>

