{{ Infobox scientist | name = Tibor Gallai | image = <!--(filename only)--> | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1912|7|15}} | birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1992|1|2|1912|7|15}} | death_place = Budapest, [[Hungary]] | nationality = [[Hungary]] | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[Eötvös Loránd University]] | alma_mater = [[Technical University of Budapest]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Dénes Kőnig]] | doctoral_students = [[László Lovász]] | known_for = [[Sylvester–Gallai theorem]] | awards = }} '''Tibor Gallai''' (born Tibor Grünwald, 15 July 1912 – 2 January 1992) was a [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] [[mathematician]]. He worked in [[combinatorics]], especially in [[graph theory]], and was a lifelong friend and collaborator of [[Paul Erdős]]. He was a student of [[Dénes Kőnig]] and an advisor of [[László Lovász]]. He was a corresponding member of the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] (1991).
== His main results == The [[Edmonds&ndash;Gallai decomposition theorem]], which was proved independently by Gallai and [[Jack Edmonds]], describes finite graphs from the point of view of matchings. Gallai also proved, with [[Arthur Milgram|Milgram]], [[Dilworth's theorem]] in 1947, but as they hesitated to publish the result, Dilworth independently discovered and published it.<ref>P. Erdős: [http://www.springerlink.com/content/n403421271440504/ In memory of Tibor Gallai], ''[[Combinatorica]]'', '''12'''(1992), 373&ndash;374.</ref>
Gallai was the first to prove the higher-dimensional version of [[van der Waerden's theorem]].
With [[Paul Erdős]] he gave a [[necessary and sufficient condition]] for a sequence to be the degree sequence of a graph, known as the [[Erdős–Gallai theorem]].
